  "prompt": "How is hashCode in Java implemented and when should I override it?",
  "response": "Let's dive into the details of `hashCode()` in Java:\n\n### Default `hashCode()` Implementation\n\nBy default, the `hashCode()` method in the `Object` class is implemented to return a unique integer for each object, typically based on the object's memory address.\n\n```java\npublic class Object {\n    public int hashCode() {\n        return System.identityHashCode(this);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n### When to Override `hashCode()`\n\nYou should override `hashCode()` when:\n1. You're overriding `equals()` method\n2. You want to use the object in hash-based collections (HashMap, HashSet)\n\n### Rules for Overriding `hashCode()`\n\n1. Consistent with `equals()`: If two objects are equal according to `equals()`, they must have the same `hashCode()`\n\n```java\npublic class Person {\n    private String name;\n    private int age;\n\n    // Proper implementation\n    @Override\n    public boolean equals(Object o) {\n        if (this == o) return true;\n        if (!(o instanceof Person)) return false;\n        Person person = (Person) o;\n        return age == person.age && \n               Objects.equals(name, person.name);\n    }\n\n    @Override\n    public int hashCode() {\n        // Use Objects.hash for multiple fields\n        return Objects.hash(name, age);\n\n        // Or manually calculate\n        // int result = name != null ? name.hashCode() : 0;\n        // result = 31 * result + age;\n        // return result;\n    }\n}\n```\n\n### Example of Why `hashCode()` Matters\n\n```java\nHashMap<Person, String> map = new HashMap<>();\nPerson p1 = new Person(\"John\", 30);\nPerson p2 = new Person(\"John\", 30);\n\nmap.put(p1, \"Value1\");\nSystem.out.println(map.get(p2)); // Will be null without proper hashCode()\n```\n\n### Best Practices\n\n1. Use prime number (typically 31) in calculation\n2. Include all significant fields in `hashCode()`\n3. Use `Objects.hash()` for simplicity\n4. Make `hashCode()` consistent with `equals()`\n\n### Common Implementation Patterns\n\n```java\n// Manual implementation\n@Override\npublic int hashCode() {\n    int result = 17;\n    result = 31 * result + (name != null ? name.hashCode() : 0);\n    result = 31 * result + age;\n    return result;\n}\n\n// Using Objects.hash() (Java 7+)\n@Override\npublic int hashCode() {\n    return Objects.hash(name, age);\n}\n```\n\n### Performance Considerations\n\n- Cache the hash code if calculation is expensive\n- Make calculation simple and fast\n\n```java\npublic class Person {\n    private String name;\n    private int age;\n    private int cachedHashCode = 0;\n\n    @Override\n    public int hashCode() {\n        if (cachedHashCode == 0) {\n            cachedHashCode = Objects.hash(name, age);\n        }\n        return cachedHashCode;\n    }\n}\n```\n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n- Always override both `equals()` and `hashCode()`\n- Ensure consistency between the two methods\n- Use `Objects.hash()` for simple implementations\n- Consider performance for complex objects\n\n### Common Mistakes to Avoid\n\n- Don't include mutable fields that can change\n- Don't make overly complex calculations\n- Ensure consistent results across program runs\n\nBy following these guidelines, you'll create robust and predictable hash code implementations that work well with Java's collection framework.",
